04602nam a22006135i 9780773555518DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735555187 a10.1515/97807735555182doi  a(DE-B1597)654724  a(OCoLC)1055049563  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV6433.C2bl56 2018 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a363.32509712231 aLivermore, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDetained :bIslamic Fundamentalist Extremism and the War on Terror in Canada /cDaniel Livermore. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPart One -- tInto the World of Open Conflict -- tInto the 1990s -- tRessam and the Eve of 9/11 -- tThe War on Terror Begins -- tAfghanistan, “Black Sites,” and the Abyss of Guantanamo Bay -- tRendition, Extraordinary Rendition, and Security Certificates -- tPart Two -- tAhmad Abou-Elmaati -- tAbdullah Almalki -- tMaher Arar -- tAbdullah Khadr -- tAbousfian Abdelrazik -- tThe Heritage of the War on Terror -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, Canadian agencies willingly collaborated in the War on Terror launched by the United States to destroy Al Qaeda. This partnership went seriously astray, however, amid a series of fundamental errors by Canadian agencies and their misplaced trust in American willingness to abide by both international and US laws against torture. As a result, numerous Canadian citizens and residents were illicitly detained abroad and subjected to suffering and mistreatment. In Detained Daniel Livermore analyzes the emergence of Islamic fundamentalist extremism and its Canadian implications, including the erroneous investigations that targeted Canadians and led to their detentions in Syria, Egypt, Pakistan, Libya, Tunisia, and Sudan. Scrutinizing the most prominent cases, he details the role of Canadian agencies in the imprisonments and relates how subsequent court cases brought the situations to light, resulting in settlements and apologies to Ahmad Abou-El-Maati, Abdullah Almalki, and Maher Arar, among others. Drawing on his experience in Canada's foreign ministry, Livermore explains how an essentially misguided War on Terror emerged and how Canadian-American cooperation went wrong. A gripping blend of memoir and meticulous research, Detained urges a more mature and rational discussion of security and intelligence issues in Canada and greater understanding of the failures of security cooperation in the decade after 9/11.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamic fundamentalismzCanada. 0aMuslimszCanadaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aNational securityzCanada. 0aRacial profiling in law enforcementzCanada. 0aSecurity, International. 0aTerrorismxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxInternational cooperation. 0aTerrorismzCanadaxPrevention. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355551840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555518/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-all